  "byline": "Tyler Cowen",
  "publishedAt": "2026-05-15T18:53:57.000Z",
  "contentHtml": "<p>1. Mikhail Fishman, <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Successor-Nemtsov-Vladimir-Decline-Modern/dp/1782277250/ref=sr_1_1?crid=3RYICE16ER4DE&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.CL-T9vNTzIvQhwuwUHesiA.RlNWrycDYde8n0KWxrK2tBAXSKB5a_sSdkhBrgHhRwA&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=The+Successor%3A+Boris+Nemtsov%2C+Vladimir+Putin%2C+and+the+Decline+of+Modern+Russia&amp;nsdOptOutParam=true&amp;qid=1778814809&amp;sprefix=the+successor+boris+nemtsov%2C+vladimir+putin%2C+and+the+decline+of+modern+russia%2Caps%2C359&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">The Successor: Boris Nemtsov, Vladimir Putin, and the Decline of Modern Russia</a>.&nbsp; One of the best books to read on how Russia moved from “had some democratic elements in place” to autocracy, on a step-by-step basis.&nbsp; The story is told using the career of Boris Nemtsov, who was assassinated in 2014, as a lens.&nbsp; The author has biases of his own, but they do not detract from what is valuable here.</p>\n<p>2. Siri Hustvedt. <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Ghost-Stories-Memoir-Siri-Hustvedt/dp/1668218941/ref=sr_1_1?crid=3LFY3OYCTVQ2K&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.qedeWcNeWGkpdjs249dylRT83KRJOuzM29EHJ5xwsytdSGl8H-El56pJvxYYUuhP6mqLSHkJV1Iyb0fUNMBeBtOgIhrB7xxHaL_qDB7NpiCsqfPvcBPjvB0EmzynghYPkYWxyoVV2GtY72kIqBjxdDl1a4VDWZrpAaiuIaJrlGsf3E0rJOf1aUVZrCTxJQXQskPfx40EEwk0Be7AqsWFlXY1DJCMkH33RvrvFGb9vVc.vfpP4rx8_Y27AIX39B37TfuEdyaWuXfYdml6YRDDbH0&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=Ghost+Stories%3A+A+Memoir&amp;qid=1778814850&amp;sprefix=ghost+stories+a+memoir%2Caps%2C479&amp;sr=8-1\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Ghost Stories: A Memoir</a>.&nbsp; About her history with her now-deceased husband Paul Auster, and how she dealt with his death.&nbsp; Moving and insightful, recommended.</p>\n<p>3. Thomas Mann, <a href=\"https://www.amazon.com/Doctor-Faustus-Oxford-Worlds-Classics/dp/0198867727/ref=sr_1_2?crid=2SG3YRFQ339SE&amp;dib=eyJ2IjoiMSJ9.8iHz5un1jV6gPubdiqjuxlZZwGgDLZ3MxLlqRdILvhB0UYDsiNH5Ll3Biumnk5SMPqKRyRwfBB_LcKBWREwzvAN0bGW3oRb5fxuL5EFuDg7xwo1T25NkMBATT82fns2LWFli2CQC6s81dahyyIlCiGlfzR028wKN9ZVe091nLISWxc5e_xyg65DyzkD2XEdrpO7Ymxx1plEKo0SAXScit2noA4Hw9EP0OuzJa6-ChyP332KC8uPCysEdqXD7Om5vzIJgb6SANkq1CmW2B4_OEFYV0Pjehrx2pq_SlV_H1xQ.oDZK2VIuKchQRTqBeNZz0ESfUk9bY0yQnqjhP3pJqBw&amp;dib_tag=se&amp;keywords=Doctor+Faustus&amp;qid=1778814882&amp;sprefix=doctor+faustus%2Caps%2C212&amp;sr=8-2\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Doctor Faustus</a>, a new translation by Ritchie Robertson.&nbsp; An imperfect, problematic work, too caught up with its own Germanness, and lacking dramatic tension.&nbsp; Still, an important work and this new translation is much better than the old one.</p>\n<p>Elsewhere, here is <a href=\"https://x.com/beeple/status/2055135873453195733\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Beeple on AI and Monet</a>, for the terminally online only.</p>",
